Republican strategy to resist Obama’s re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies in order to combat election fraud.
The Brennan Center, however, views the latter as a myth, arguing that fraud in elections in the United States is more rare than death by lightning.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions have partly discredited the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have since 2009 enacted laws that complicate the registration or voting process.
This phenomenon took on new dimensions after the November 2010 elections, which brought 675 new seats to Republicans in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills were passed in 2011 alone, restricting voting rights in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require the voter to present an identity card with a photograph and proof of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register voters on the day of expression of will, and withdraw the right to vote from citizens with criminal records.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present an identity card with a photograph.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
In 2008, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of Indian law.
The Republican authorities have rushed to extend the practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated legislation requiring voters to present photo identification cards in 34 states.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as a health insurance card.
Indeed, 11 per cent of American citizens, that is, 21 million people who have reached the voting age, do not have an identity card with a photograph issued by their state government.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
The cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds $100.
New restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
Indeed, 25 per cent of African-Americans, 15 per cent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 per cent of citizens over 65 years of age and 20 per cent of voters between 18 and 29 years of age do not have the required photo identification.
But that's not all.
Voters who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates are not allowed to use a photo ID issued by their educational institution in several states.
At the same time, the same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for Republicans, to use the cards issued by these clubs for voting.
Until 2004, no state required proof of American citizenship to vote.
This was the first time that such a requirement had been introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are apparently aimed at limiting the vote of Latin Americans.
Two thirds of Latin American voters are believed to vote in favour of the Democratic Party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators initiated laws to abolish voter registration on polling day in eight states.
They have also limited the right of individuals or groups to assist those wishing to register.
This limitation did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to register some 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17 per cent decline in the registration rate of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, national legislators in five other states have enacted laws aimed at shortening the period of early voting.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33 per cent of the voters who voted early were African Americans, although the latter represented only 13 per cent of the total number of voters in the state.
The same was true of Latin Americans.
Representing only 11 per cent of the electorate, they constituted 24 per cent of the citizens who voted early.
Unlike the whites, who made up 76% of the voters, only 46% of the voters were early voters.
Of course, Democrat legislators and their supporters are actively opposed to the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several draft laws have been re-issued by Democratic Governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended with the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This has reduced the negative impact in part.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the submission of an identity card with a photograph.
Nevertheless, the new rules that have come into effect will undoubtedly impede the exercise of the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics from Democrats condemn the bias of the laws that have been passed, as they clearly seek to influence the 2012 election results in key states.
The Brennan Center ' s 2011 report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 out of 270 votes in the electoral college to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with confidence that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential elections.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions have partly discredited the system of American democracy.
