Higgs' boson in detail.
Last summer, the report that scientists may have been able to locate Higgs' boson caused a real agitation - and not without cause.
It's believed that this boson explains the mass of all the particles in the universe, not a lot.
In addition, it is the last particle predicted in the Standard Model - our best, or in any case the “least imperfect” description of the nature and behaviour of matter - but which has not previously been detected in an experimental way.
But physics isn't quite sure it's the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we're dealing with a really new particle and that it's very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, the new data presented this week at a major physical convention in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although some data is not yet available for full confidence.
Let's just say we're talking about the Higgs boson, because the odds are minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is, in this world, one law absolutely inevitable, saying that two things can't end up in the same place at the same time.
There's no way around this rule, don't try too hard, or you'll hurt yourself.
But although particle physics is a rather strange world, it also has one law of this nature: the principle of Paulie's exclusion, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same moment in time, if they are in the same “quantum state” is basically a state in some of its characteristics.
On this basis, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens, called farmers, who are prudently subject to the Paulie principle.
In another, bosons, an abominable gang of anarchists, who have no respect for anything — at least this principle — mean that they may find themselves in the same place at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Laboratory's Particle Adventure, these bosons in turn are divided into two groups: Mesons, which we're not going to talk about here, and "particles of power", which spread the basic forces of nature and to which the Higgs boson is in some way related.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all exotic creatures as thought to be.
In fact, if you're able to read this chronicle, it's because of one incredibly banal boson: photon, or part of the light, which is an electromagnetic courier.
Indeed, when one particle with an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it breaks the electromagnetic field in this particular place, like a stone thrown into a pond.
An electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.) is produced from this “violation”, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons of “power carriers”.
More stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with the only difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be violated in order for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; in order to excite it, you have to achieve very, very high energy, as if it were a frozen pond whose surface could only be shaken by a very large stone.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator, like the one that's operating in CERN, the Large Adrone Collider, which is a 27-kilometre-diameter ring, to achieve such huge energy.
An electromagnetic field analogy is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and the mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with an electromagnetic field.
Some, such as magnets, interact, others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on the fridge.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like photon, by the way) do not.
So, what's "can bring" all this research, is Ms. Plamondon asking?
In science, they are used to test the correctness of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to sense a discrepancy between observations and predictions of the SM.
In addition, some of them yearn for such a discrepancy to emerge, so the slightest discrepancy can open the door to "new physics" and shut up some of the Model's holes.
The latter, to say the least, still has significant flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (oi!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oi-oi!).
But we haven't found any differences in CERN yet.
Impact
It is more difficult to predict the benefits of these studies for the daily life of the average person, but it would be a mistake to assume that they do not exist.
See, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research in Bell's labs couldn't even imagine what revolution their work would bring.
They anticipated their applications in science, but nothing more.
Indeed, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell's Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the previous ones were impulse) in 1962, said that the laser was originally considered more of a "laboratory gadget".
Imagine...
In addition, an application could be found for tools accompanying the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle, during his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although not its original purpose, now serves as an eye for all digital cameras in the world and has won the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Great Adron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that everything can be.
