Pay and sell without the help of banks - Bitcoin
The exact opposite of the current monetary exchange based on central banks, numbered transactions between the receiving parties with fees for processing them.
Moreover, as often happens with these technologies, a political vision is evident: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto, is both a virtual currency (but converted into dollars, euros ...) and a protected BitTorrent-type exchange protocol that allows file-sharing between participants at the same level.
Some 200,000 transactions have already been registered with 15,000 computers online.
Several thousand sites take bitcoins for donations or as a means of payment.
The rate of the Bitcoin, reaching a maximum of $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later, before returning to about ten dollars today (the rates are listed on Bitcoincharts.com).
It's nothing compared to the world's exchange of real money or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) was interested in the system in its virtual currency report published in October.
He describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "like ordinary currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as “credits” used to promote video games that are earned during the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchanges are always controlled and processed by a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are both account holders, auditors, issuers of currency, buyers and sellers.
How does the network function?
Each transaction between two users actually occurs between two e-mail addresses, like an e-mail.
Only for each new payment can the user choose another address, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information relating to this transaction is electronically signed using a double key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that bitcoins used in the transaction do exist in a public ledger distributed throughout the network.
A key step is the registration of a new transaction in this book.
It goes through a mathematical task sent to computers, which, like a temporary central bank, has the privilege of adding this new line.
This is the hash phase of the file, that is, the conversion of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" all together.
The aim is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number has been found, other nodes can easily verify that it is correct.
The transaction is thus unbrokenly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user would want to pay twice the same amount of money in less than ten minutes, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed because they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solved the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the award is regularly shared in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divided to one hundred million, leaving a further reserve...
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in computing power.
