Poland and space.
Last week, at a ministerial meeting of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has participated actively in a number of Agency projects over the following years.
But the way to space Poland started a long time ago.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts had been involved in space flights, but that was not always understood.
I recall, for example, the lecture given by A. Sternfeld on 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which presented ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction into Space".
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, and after several years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltry and André Luis Hirsch Prize in France for "Introduction into Space".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and space science.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned space promoter, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the opposite side of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a rocket - driven railway drone was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea remained unknown, as did the details of the draft.
It's not even clear that a missile should have been used to disperse or to brake the trolley.
The only news about this nonsense is from the press of that era.
In 1933, Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The study was carried out by the Weapons Technology Section in cooperation with Professors Mázyslav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzytski.
The existing material shows that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket proposed by the engineer Rogozinsky appeared in a specialized press, and the following year the work of the author Lelivi-Kjiblocsky's “Aerial torpedo and aerial bomb” came out.
Both projects were designed for the military use of missile engines.
Before the war itself, all military missile projects were handled by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all activities.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work ended because of the outbreak of war.
The next space science paper appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first reference to society is in the November 1954 issue of the magazine “Problems”, which publishes four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich offered to organize a society that would be involved in space activities.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PAA) has tried to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951) and has been a member of the International Astronautical Federation since the fall.
The following year, the first President of PAA, Kazimez Zarankevich (1902-1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the RPA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful RM meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologyzna), which was the first Polish missile to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first was launched on October 10, 1958.
The missile, which could pass 1,800 metres, was about 80 cm long and weighing less than 5 kg.
An improved version of the RM-1A was subsequently built, and a two-stage RM-2 missile was tested on the Bledova Desert in the summer of 1959.
The missile was about 1.4 metres long and weighed approximately 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile could have crossed 14.5 km and its mission was to observe the high wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The first RM-type missiles were inherited by the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed to be two-stage, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which varied in size for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A missile had a volume of 0.4 litres, the Meteor-1V had a volume of 0.34 litres and the Meteor-1C had a volume of 0.62L.
All three types had a maximum range of 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 missile was developed at the Aviation Institute and its first flight test began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 missile, with a launch weight of 380 kg, was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The versions of Meteor 2N and Meteor 3 were then built.
Mention should also be made of Poland's accession to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the COSPAR national committee two years later.
In addition, as part of the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
