Inflating balloons, bananas and circus rules
The portal www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts an annual survey of the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to announce a competition for "the most absurd decision or project from the EU workshop".
“We were inspired by this latest event in which the EU plans to adopt a 40 per cent quota for women in the administration of large European companies”, said the Prava questionnaire organizer Patrick Nager.
Among the absurdities already put forward is the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to combine the rate of premiums for men and women.
So far, women have enjoyed life insurance benefits because they are objectively less at risk for insurance companies.
"Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be put forward by people for the competition before the end of this year.
The vote itself will take place before the end of February 2013, said Nager.
The controversial EU regulations include, for example, the mandatory addition of bio-components to fuel, resulting in damage to nature, and the prohibition of the use of reliable mercury thermometers only because they contain relatively small quantities of hazardous substances, or the directive on the size of the chicken cage, which has resulted in a substantial increase in the cost of eggs this year.
The actual prohibition of the use of the term “butter oil” or the removal of classic bulbs from the market was also criticized.
Quality bananas must be 14 centimeters long.
The pan-European machinery often makes a decision under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually protected by a State or group of States (in this way the Czech Republic now even threatens to defend the demands of its banks).
The interests of the lobby are as follows: for example, bananas of the highest quality in the EU were to reach a length of 14 centimetres and did not dare to display "agnostic curvature".
In doing so, the European Commission was justified by the fact that it only harmonizes existing fragmented national rules, which complicated trade.
The EU, despite the resistance of some States, has nevertheless relaxed the standards for fruit and vegetables, arguing that existing directives will lead to waste of products.
Last year’s EU regulation that selling balloons must be accompanied by a warning that children under the age of eight cannot inflate them without the supervision of adults may also be a candidate for a poll.
The EU has turned to American studies according to which balloons in the game are a potential cause of death of children by strangulation.
This restriction now applies to children under 14 years of age, who are not allowed to blow into carnage.
Funny ideas are born at home, too.
The rule of European officials themselves is absurd: anyone who holds an official position in the EU cannot, given the sensitivity of the topic for Greece, use the name Macedonia, but should instead say “BURM” (the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The Bankovnípoplatky.com portal, in cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, has proposed for voting, in addition to some of the absurd rules mentioned above, such as the EU regulation on the amount of food stocks on the territory of a member State.
The EU has established a maximum amount of food that may be available in the Czech Republic on the date of its accession to the European Union.
Subsequently, the Czech Republic, for example, exceeded the prescribed amounts of canned mushrooms, for which it was liable to a heavy fine.
The questionnaire organizers were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea and the idea of providing subsidies for applications for subsidies.
But these ideas came from Prague, not Brussels.
"We are at a disadvantage because we have no sea.
We ask for compensation from the European Union,” said then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palace (CSDP) in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he pointed out that there was a high yield of grain in the country and, as a result of so-called intervention purchases, the State had full stores of stocks that had to be removed.
For the fact that the Czech Republic is far from ports, the EU, according to Palas, should have paid us hundreds of millions of euros.
As a result, the European Commission met the Czech Republic by organizing a tender for grain from landlocked countries.
Grant grants were offered to villages by the Ministry of Regional Development, led by Minister Pavel Nemz (US-DEU), in particular, such grants were to be drawn up for grants from Brussels.
EU: Curious orders are the exception
While regulations in member States are easily criticized, the EU’s efforts to regulate as well as to improve the functioning and development of the EU are, in the view of many experts, more worthy of recognition.
A serious problem, in the view of the experts, is the drawing of EU grants for projects that do not have even a hint of anything in common with deepening European integration, but that have been achieved by member States in the budget discussions.
It is emotional among Czechs that, as in other EU countries, the Czech Republic should fight in Brussels for the right to specific identification of its traditional products, and it does not always win this competition.
Although the Czechs, after six years of fighting the Germans and the Austrians, retained the name "Olomowsky cheeses", the "Tuzem rum", whose tradition in our country dates back to the 19th century, was to be renamed "Tuzemak".
The only products that can be called rum are cane distillate, not sugar beet.
The official list of EU-registered products, along with the world-famous “feta” and “gorgondzola” cheeses, the Marzipan of German Lubek or Parm ham, have already included, for example, Carlovar swarms, the Gorgeous and Trashbon Karp and the Champ.
The EU’s trademark can also be proud of the Pardubic carrot and the Montagnard straws.
People want me to protect the republic, but I'm an amateur, says Okamura.
Mr. Senator, how does a man want to run for president?
I don't think about becoming a senator or president myself.
If everything was working in the country without a problem, I wouldn't be running anywhere.
But I can't stand to see the country embezzling over the last 20 years, there being thieves, raising people's taxes and retirement age.
I had no ambition to be a politician.
But when I see something I don't like, I try to find a way to change it.
And since I'm 40 years old and I'm an independent person who's not a member of any party, I have no other way of influencing things than running for senator or president.
You got into the Senate, but soon you went to the presidential castle.
Don't you turn your back on the people who chose you?
I always said I'd fight for the presidential castle depending on the outcome of the Senate election.
Later, I made it clear that if I were to be elected senator, I would run for president.
My goal is not a position, a position is a tool that I can use to give effect to my views.
That's why I need the greatest influence and the greatest authority.
But the problem is not only that as a nation, we murmur in our own bar or TV, but we are ready to trample on anyone who tries to make a difference.
To this is added the media, which defame a person, and which confuse freedom of speech with freedom of lie.
For example, I was told that I was giving bribes to journalists, or that I was Girgi Paroubek's advisor.
Let's move on to your views.
You began the fight for the presidential castle by talking about the material and criminal responsibility of politicians and about the return of property declarations worth more than 20 million.
To do so, the law must be changed.
You don't have that power as president, and only an entire Senate can propose laws.
How do you want to do that?
When I lobbied as a citizen for the guided tour to become a free enterprise, it was moved forward.
The problem is politics – when someone comes with a good offer on the left or right, they are deliberately obstructed, and it deters citizens.
As an independent, non-partisan individual, I have a much greater potential to receive support from all parliamentary parties.
My advantage is that I can take from each party what is best for our country and apply it without a look at dogmats.
