The MVRDV architects prove that real adventures aren't just in the imagination - in the case of Speykenisse and his recently built Book Mountain - 2 photos
"I think this building is fun, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again," says Lisette Verhaig, passing on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist in a nearby large enterprise, says, "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I ask myself, why do we need another library today?
Everyone has Internet, iPad, and e-books.
No one's voluntarily going to these old-fashioned libraries now, right?
Speykenisse, a small bedroom under Rotterdam, has an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
In order to combat this unfortunate situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to build seven fictional bridges, which are depicted on euro notes, in the form of painted miniatures made of concrete concrete.
The success of this educational initiative has been modest.
And that's when the city's fathers realized that they had the only chance to beat the statistics: build a library here!
Vene Maas of the Rotterdam architectural bureau MVRDV, a master of bold column charts and author of witty, sometimes cynical, structures, took up the task with his usual unchallengedness and appeared at a competitive audition in 2003 with five books under the mouse and a smirk on his face.
And while the members of the jury were puzzled to look around and shrug their shoulders, the daring Maas laid down a pyramid in size from his original gift and concluded his speech in defence of his project with the words, "Dear citizens!"
Here it is, my proposal: "The Book Mountain" in Speikenisse, the so-called Bukenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain, worth 30 million euros, grew.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground garage, supermarket, postage and several adjacent housing units and townships with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the Book Mountain was awarded the second award of the 2012 Best Library of the Netherlands.
The project also participates in the 2012 Dutch National Wood Competition.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which had previously been able to offer nothing but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall whose white facades suggested a milk factory, became richer for one contemporary piece of architecture.
But most importantly, the first cultural public building in the town's history has appeared in Speykenisse.
A Long Way to the Book
First impression: Eldorado's book room under a cheese cap.
There's only one elevator in the middle of a mountain range, because real fans of architecture and reading would prefer to explore the area on foot.
Exposed from all sides - light and easy to see, brick floors and elegant street lights unmistakably create a sense of public urban square.
The urban environment has been re-established perfectly.
Looking at benches, dogs, and soccer boys and girls.
And there are books, books, books everywhere.
"Normally bookshelves stand along facades, and in the middle there is a large dark hall, usually uncomfortable and faceless," says Vini Maas.
We put the classic head-to-head configuration and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The inner area of the bookmount has been ably used: the centre houses offices, Internet libraries, a chess club, an environmental centre and technical facilities.
The black bookshelves, which serve as walls, parapets, and stairwells, are particularly encouraging.
Their appearance, texture, and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and builders are lost in their guesses as to what this unknown material is.
“We sought to work with secondary materials,” explains Yop Trauborst, the project manager representing the Spikeniss community, as required by the standard.
And one day, at a farm in France, we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years now, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, artificial fibrous material of millimetre thickness has been used as a root lining.
It's cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons and can then be discarded.
For the library, this painting, for the first time in such volumes, was compressed in a panel of four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbauplasty (KLP) turns into dark, homogeneous, durable material, which smells a little like a new car and a little sneaker.
They're taking 105 steps to the top.
Those who travel nearly 500 metres in length will be rewarded in a literary café not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquets and wood chips in pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and above all about the correct humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
Cost of a new soul
"It's hard to believe, but this building, despite many glass surfaces, is a model environmental project," says Trouborst.
The heat of the ground shall be used for heating and cooling.
Although the Book Mountain is under a glass cap, even on clear days the sun enters only briefly.
Large flatwood farms, perpendicular to the glass facades, provide shade and absorb most of the sunlight.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The remaining protection is provided by fully automatic roll curtains.
Stefan Spermon, the IT skeptic mentioned earlier, has already visited a new library.
Lisette Verhaig was here as well.
And also a Chinese traditional medicine teacher, Cynthia Bogard, who called Bukenberg "the soul of the Speykenisse that was long missed."
Reason: A few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate a book from his own congregation.
These books were supposed to fill empty spaces on the shelves of a library that was not yet fully staffed; at that time, there were 70,000 books.
The idea worked.
The shelves are locked up.
"There's nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Vini Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident now has some connection to this new house.
Everyone knows his book is part of this building.
Even if it only serves as an ornament.
The MVRDV has thus been able to accomplish the royal task, which in the professional jargon is called the creation of identity.
Speykenisse wrote his literary history.
And may they be very young and uneducated.
It's just the starting point for building an identity.
Sabo: "The Germans must play a more important role."
Germany abstained in the vote on recognition of Palestine.
Stephen Sabo, an expert in US-Europe relations, believes that Berlin, by doing so, is balancing on a narrow diplomatic track.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first indicated that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also abstained in the voting on the no-fly zone.
NATO eventually implemented the proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The point is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, from a policy that the US has so-called ruled to a German foreign policy itself.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a coherent and unified policy.
So the Germans are back between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they're just feeling their part, but they're on the road to "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy as it is pursued by France or the United Kingdom.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from the German perspective?
It is a willingness to take a position in the national interest that is not dependent on the position of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, i.e. on exports and links to certain regions, such as Russia, China, or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests were largely different from those of other major States, and Germany must therefore protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has major markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be careful not to offend the public and elites in Arab countries.
In any case, it plays its part.
But I wouldn't put too much emphasis on it, it's not entirely one-sided.
But in any case, it plays an important role in German calculations.
Did Germany harm its relations with the US by abstaining from making important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that in Europe, and even in the United States, understanding of the German position prevails.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
This signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are different views about the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
On the contrary, the US has clearly supported the veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European states?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that Obama’s government, deep down, has a sufficient understanding of the European position.
But, of course, due to the local political situation, the Government cannot openly adopt such a position.
I believe that the substantive differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, notice that Obama is not at all thrilled with Netanyahu’s politics.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of a crucial partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for Germans to have a single, consistent European policy, but it is not now.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and have to act instead on their own vision.
That's what they do with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
Understandably, this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they should play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it really take over?
Or is the lead still hard on Germany?
Germany has not yet become accustomed to this, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is always difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis — every time Germany takes on an important role, a variety of anti-German feelings manifest themselves.
Germans don't just deal with it.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much worse position than the US.
It must take into account a wide range of neighbours and opinions, which is not easy.
So, the US influence in European politics is constantly waning, but at the moment the EU is not filling this vacuum, who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a greater role.
Even if you don't like it, it's unpleasant, or it increases your dislike, it's life.
Stephen Sabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, where academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly study the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, which specializes in German politics, US foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
Trademark Security in China: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous trademark, Polo Ralph Lauren is also.
But what is Armani Polo?
It is an entirely officially registered name in China that has nothing to do with the firms from whose names it is formed.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names bring a claim.
But it is still unclear whether they will be able to defend their rights.
“Foreigners are finding it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,” says Thomas Pattloh, a lawyer for Taylor Wessing, who specializes in trademark violations in the Far East.
My desk shows up every week on a new case of this kind.
Simulators need only add a couple of letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So from Gucci it's Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada, you can register Prada-Kny.
In the same way, German enterprises, such as the Puma manufacturer of sports goods, are legally copied.
Pattloch opens a folder with the records of the Trademark Office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, the Chinese company registered the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also used the name of the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
The fact that the Chinese are world champions of copying and intellectual property infringement is well known.
In large cities, there are multi-storey stores selling almost exclusively counterfeits.
However, the Pattloch cases were not the same; on instructions from his trustees, he was opposed to Chinese enterprises being formally authorized by the trademark registry to use a name that was already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it the Ban Minpei, the Marka Passenger.
It's a word associated with "ban Dakuan."
That's what they call women who hunt rich men.
Chinese authorities do not plead guilty
"It's detrimental to business, it needs to be fought," Pattloch is convinced.
"The brand is blurred, the unique position is lost, the image is badly damaged."
The financial losses and procedural costs in the affected industries are estimated at millions, especially in the case of high-value copying products.
According to CLSA, China, with a sales volume of Euro15 billion per year, is the third largest and fastest growing luxury market.
However, the removal of questionable records from the trademark register is difficult and costly.
The trial can last up to nine years, with an unclear outcome.
Pattloch describes the cases in which the court dismissed the claims, as after a long period of time the disputed name became a “market reality”.
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he will even have to pay the plagiarizer because he damaged his trademark in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules here.
There are also famous graphics cases.
In 2009, Daimler lost a litigation with the Sany manufacturer, a company that had recently acquired the Putzmeister concrete pump company.
So the Chinese still have the right to use the Mercedes-like emblem.
The company that bought Volvo was originally using a blue-and-white logo that resembled BMW; the process was successful, Geely had to change it.
In China, Lacoste, a fashion producer, lost to simulators from Hong Kong and Singapore, who had a famous crocodile looking the other way.
The Chinese authorities don't think they're guilty.
The Trademark Registration Office of CMMO in Beijing confirms that there were difficulties in 2010 due to lack of staff and facilities.
But last year, there was a "return from business emergency to normal."
Thus, the number of pending appeals cases decreased by 22 per cent.
Almost 57,000 such cases were closed, 75 per cent more than last year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending in the office.
It's expensive to fight.
As is so often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, CTC received more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This record means that China has led the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive time, reporting by the agency.
The same applies to the total number of valid trademarks, only 5.5 million.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan of fees were paid.
Simplisticly, this means that each registration costs an average of 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
It is worth many times more to challenge, as the case of the German family enterprise Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the concern has been fighting against the Chinese plagiarizer.
The Germans succeeded in eliminating their illegal production of fake auto parts.
However, the simulator reserved Chinese trademark rights to Freudenberg.
This was a failure of its own, as the surnames in Germany are not protected, says Hanno Ventzler, chairman of the Board of Directors of Freedenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
And the trademark authority of CTMO rejected the Munich claim.
True, Freudenberg won in both of the following instances, but the opposing side is still fighting.
We need to be alert.
The matter was currently before the Supreme Court.
Ventzler hopes to bring the matter to a good conclusion and commends the professionalism of the courts.
But he also says, "The process is extremely expensive and takes up a lot of time, money and nerves."
Internal costs are hardly accounted for, and the firm's records have even had to be reviewed from 100 years ago to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg unsuccessfully offered the opposing party a “greater six-digit amount in euros” for a settlement.
"It's clear from here how much it costs us," Ventzler says.
The dangers of the Far East threaten to move even to Europe.
That is, if the simulators register unprotected trademarks there.
For example, a Chinese manufacturer in Germany wanted to register the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The concert had long ceased production in those areas, but had nevertheless been able to prevent registration.
"You need to be on your guard," says Ventzler.
Both he and Pattloch counsel recommend that German businesses be very careful with China.
