The city is overburdened with transport and at its best, and steel barriers have been erected since Monday, cutting several key highways to the capital and causing road chaos.
However, this was not done to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from reaching the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will wear a presidential tie and take over the country.
He has a difficult task ahead of him.
Mexico had achieved good economic performance under the administration of Felipe Calderón, which was now relinquishing its powers, but the country had become mired in the war on drugs, which had claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
“My Government declares its readiness to fight violence to the people of Mexico”, Mr. Peña Nieto told President Barack Obama in the Oval Office of the White House earlier this week.
I am going to propose a new security strategy that will enable us to achieve that goal.
Prior to such statements, Mr. Peña Nieto ' s political career with the President of the United States developed as Governor of his home state of Mexico.
In his homeland, in the densely populated and vast state surrounding the capital, views were divided on the new leader.
A Direct Man
In the Idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, he is remembered warmly.
Residents have paid tribute to the revitalization of tourism, the development of resorts and the construction of infrastructure.
One of the new highways built by Mr. Peña Nieto, which is quite different from those with pits and pits that were previously built at the site, can reach the city.
His name tags are on the modern sports centre building and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
“We place his hopes in real and serious change,” his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, a state congressman from Peña Nieto’s Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that are so urgently needed by our country, particularly in the areas of security and economic development.
After 81 years of continuous rule, the PRI party was replaced by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the president's palace, Los Pinos, the party has high hopes for Enrique Peña Nieto.
In addition, he refutes the allegations of lack of substance made by the opposition to the new President.
He is very direct and very committed to his vision of the future of the country.
He's an excellent statesman, and above all, a man who can listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of a former governor.
The municipality of Nesaualkoyotl, also known as Ciudad Nessa, is the most striking contrast with the powerful streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under motorway relays, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also severe.
Earlier this year, troops had been mobilized to curb drug gangs in those areas; violence against women was particularly acute.
Several dozen bodies of murdered women have been found in the desert near an extensive dump in the last two years alone.
More than a thousand women were killed in the state of Mexico during the governorship of Mr. Peña Nieto, a figure significantly higher than in the notorious violent city of Ciudad Juárez, whose name became negative when it came to the murder of innocent women.
According to Mr. Peña Nieto ' s opponents, he could at best be said to have been unable to cope with the issue of the killing of women during his tenure as Governor.
At worst, his administration was accused of completely ignoring the problem.
Inhabitant of a concrete house similar to most of the houses in this dilapidated area, Irinaya Buendia struggles to contain tears by showing me pictures of her late daughter Mariana Luna.
Mariana officially committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her partner killed her.
"When I got to her house, it looked like her body was washed before," recalls Ms. Buendia.
There were signs that she had been beaten and her body was already hardened.
Mariana's mother recounts the story, and the portrait of her daughter looks at us from the wall, where she hangs next to the crucifix, where only one word is written: justice.
That, they said, was the case with the family.
"State officials treated me like an old gossip who was dissatisfied with the troublemaker.
They want people to just take faith in everything they say and keep quiet.
But it's wrong, you can't, especially when there's so many irregularities and flaws around here," she says.
When President Peña Nieto wears a presidential tie on Saturday, he will take on a heavy responsibility with her.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico had been affected by violent crimes, and the new President had promised to make the solution of that problem a priority during his reign.
"I hope he'll be the same president as the governor," says Olver, a congressman from Valle de Bravo from the PRI party.
But that is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nes fear most.
Bradley Manning didn't complain of ill-treatment, pleads charges.
The prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's allegations about poor conditions of detention.
The hearing focused on Manning ' s stay at the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's conditions of detention were harsh.
The U.S. Army is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, had not taken many opportunities to file a complaint for ill-treatment, which he claimed he had suffered while in military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Mede, Maryland, the Military Prosecutor, Major Ashden Fein, stated that records of weekly visits to Manning by prison authorities during the nine months of his detention in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the defence motion to dismiss Manning on the grounds that his conditions of detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment was conducted the day after Manning stated that he had intended to commit suicide while in detention.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During the hearing on Friday, Prosecutor Fain, together with Manning, reviewed the reports that had been completed after the administration ' s visits to Manning during his stay at Quantico Prison, where he was held in strict confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Fain asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he considered the treatment of himself by the prison administration to be “excellent” and the general conditions of detention to be “very professionally organized”.
The reports examined do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning's being specifically asked about the conditions of his detention, Fane claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concern about the problems and that the authorities who visited him had discussed the problems with him and stated that they would be dealt with but not recorded in writing.
"They recorded "no problem" (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring it up in the conversation," Manning says.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lindh, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his ill-treatment in January 2011 at a meeting of the commission considering the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting, he wanted him to be removed from the “injury warning” regime and to ease the conditions of detention.
The military authorities explained that the limited detention regime, which was lower than the surveillance regime for suicide prevention, had been introduced for the protection of the prisoner as well as for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm all right so they can cancel the injury prevention regime... so my life would improve, from my point of view," Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified to his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to a naval prison in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thought of suicide in Kuwait, and that he had lost consciousness one day because of the heat.
He explained that it's psychologically hard not to know how your fate is handled and what's going on in the outside world.
"My world has come down to Camp Arifjan base, up to the size of my prison," said Manning on Thursday.
- I thought I was gonna die in that cage."
While in Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day - alone.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only his mattress, blanket, flippers, some clothes and glasses.
He says he tried to move, because sleeping or even sleeping in the daytime prohibited the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, he was constantly struck in the eyes by light entering the outside of the camera.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned around in bed at night, he said that he was woken up and forced to turn on his back.
Manning ' s lawyer formally objected to Manning ' s ill-treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas.
Furthermore, on Friday, the judge asked Manning about a statement he had made during his testimony on Thursday that, after one night he had been forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico, he had been forced to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners at the morning inspection.
Manning stated that he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
In response to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he should throw a blanket to cover his back, but admitted that no one had directly ordered him to throw it.
On Thursday, Manning stated that he had been forced to sleep naked the previous night because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer that he could use a pair of panties or flippers to hurt himself, but he didn't.
That night, according to Manning's testimony, his underwear, flippers and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account what he had been through during his detention and significantly reduce his sentence if Manning was found guilty by a military court, which was to start his case early next year.
The defence stated that it planned to ask Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes and to challenge other charges as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and it is expected that the prosecution will insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was detained in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the detention of detainees under the strictest possible regime.
The charges brought against Manning include aiding and abetting the enemy, unlawful assistance in the disclosure of data on the Internet, the transmission of information relating to national defence and the theft of State property or documents.
If he is convicted on all counts of the indictment, he may face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is a Mexican American story.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of a lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American origin are torn between two cultures.
During my recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrival corridor, approached the border control area and froze on the spot.
The signs indicated two lines: one for Mexiconos (Mexicans), the other for Extraanjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds without knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called a Mexican my whole life.
It's just a conditional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends in New York think they're Italian.
Later, I discussed the complex design of "American of Mexican origin".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's home country, there was no need for conditional names or complex designs.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask or answer questions.
But my vocabulary is poorer than the speakers, and I can't get rid of the American accent.
That's why I got my American passport and became a line for Extranjeros.
I recalled that story a few days ago when the newly elected President of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The issues on the agenda of the Presidents of those countries were immigration, drugs and trafficking.
President Peña Nieto was eager to speak of the recovery of the Mexican economy, which would make it possible for Mexicans to remain in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to enter into a partnership agreement with the US and Canada and create a North American trading bloc like the EU.
In addition, President Peña Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and long-standing matter.
Most Americans never thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848 and forced its leaders to give up half of their territory at gunpoint.
But Mexicans have been thinking for centuries, not minutes, and seeing reminders of those events in everything.
So when only a US statesman utters a word of criticism toward Mexico, the press and the elites of Mexican society immediately complain that Americans are encroaching on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And Montesuma's descendants are filled with militancy.
Mexico’s most difficult relationship with over 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States is, however, the most difficult.
Do you want to talk about resentment?
That's enough.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities in this country, and those who do not.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver, or San Antonio, so many people of Mexican origin for one reason only: at some point in their family history, someone, father or grandfather, was unable to realize himself in Mexico and had to go north.
Most of the time, they were Mexicans of a certain type - brown, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We're their descendants, and we remember that.
That's not how Mexico sees it.
Today, our lives are the embodiment of America's dream, and we've been in good schools and we've got good jobs, but we can remember that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know which country to consider as its own.
United States of America.
We also know that most members of the Mexican elite and ruling class don't like us.
We tell them the same thing.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class people, as fake Mexicans.
We do not speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence for them is due to failure.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We wouldn't be behind a silk curtain right now, finding a full life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States when she was a child, which reminds me that there are certain tensions between real Mexicans and Mexican-Americans - Mexicans are more aware of their national identity, and Mexican-Americans are offended.
She's a U.S. citizen and thinks she belongs to both of these countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintances of Mexican American origin do not feel that they belong to any of them.
We're listening to the Mexican band Los Tigers del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
Getting the best of the two worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we're Americans.
And in the United States, they call us Mexicans.
Now, as I learned during my trip, as if our relationship was not yet complicated enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to re-establish relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican Americans to work as Mexican ambassadors and represent their interests in the US.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
It's not gonna work.
Too much resentment in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, corruption and drug trafficking, many of us don't think this country is so beautiful.
I'm sorry, but deal with it yourself, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still angry about how they treated their relatives in Mexico recently.
Yeah.
I think we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
A ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
The usual senseless debate over who started it; many buildings were turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis were killed; for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip fell in the vicinity of the Israeli capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, while Israelis and Palestinians have become hopelessly entangled in their eternal conflict, changes have taken place in the Middle East.
This may be viewed in different ways, but the events of the Arab Spring have encircled many established realities in the rebel storm, and the Palestinians and the Israelis have not been able to stay away from the whirlwind that shocked the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons for hope that this deadly impasse will be overcome.
War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation does not give cause for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on 21 November, were to be implemented, the clashes this week only strengthened the positions of the forcemen on both sides.
The leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will claim that they forced Israel to retreat despite its losses.
Despite the fact that some faction leaders have been destroyed and 1.7 million people blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled parts of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new powerful and rich friends.
The reborn regional leader of Turkey, once Israel’s closest ally among Muslim countries, has supported Hamas; its example has been followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic States in the Persian Gulf.
Hamas’s solemn supporters have announced the establishment of an Islamist crescent around Israel, from Lebanon to the north, where Hezbollah’s militia is ruling, to Syria, where increasingly Islamic rebels are about to overthrow the power of Bashar Assad, and further to Jordan, where the King’s power is threatened by Hamas’s allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood movement was strengthened under President Mohammed Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator with little emphasis on support for Hamas.
On the contrary, Muslim brothers are an organization much like Hamas, and their leaders are more likely to be populist.
In future diplomatic positions, Hamas can become a meaningful player whose voice cannot be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the hardline line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli Iron Dome missile system has borne the cost of its development and successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
Israeli citizens can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the US has remained committed; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for starting the last round of violence.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, particularly under the Binyamin Netanyahu Government, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Although approximately 30 Israelis had been killed by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip since 2004, Israel had managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, partly through the wall, which entered the West Bank, a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian State, and protected Jewish settlements, which continued to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the 22 January elections - has joined forces with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very comfortable.
What is the point of condoning the Palestinians and giving them their own State?
If they hand over all the power in the West Bank, would they not start firing rockets from there towards Israel, as their brothers in the Gaza Strip do?
It's better to keep them behind the wall and severely suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
The supporters of the hardline may win; however, their calculations may be refuted by the Arab spring.
While the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priorities will be internal problems.
Israel’s defense budget is larger than all its Arab neighbours combined.
The outbreak of war with a regional super-Power is unlikely to help Arab Governments to strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel must, no less, take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change takes place in Arab countries, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a time bomb that will eventually explode in Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
Reprisals were already undermining the foundations of a democratic order in a Jewish State, and the demographic dimension — the growth of the Arab population — only exacerbated those problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to be paid for by the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need external momentum
The only solution remains that has been relentlessly called for by sound representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two States and Israeli concessions of territories in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not too overwhelming in the short term, that a ceasefire will enable other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, long overdue in its decision to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, are more than ever in a position to persuade Hamas to accept the borders of the Jewish State that have been adopted since 1967, given the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries must also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
That would do more to create a Palestinian State than the forthcoming United Nations vote, which could result in recognition of Palestinian virtual statehood.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
When he returned to the White House, he continued to show reluctance to engage in the problem.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the Uniform Carcase Act has entered into force.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and images of diseased body parts are contrasted with sad green boxes that are the same for all cigarette stamps.
The first worldwide Australian law on the same-type packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products has entered into force, replacing logos and coloured brands with a similar box of sad olives with creepy images of diseased parts of the body and images of children whose health has been compromised by smoking by their parents.
In addition to the various images and inscriptions that warn of the harm of smoking, the only difference between the packs that are mandatory from this Saturday is the names of stamps that are printed in the same small print.
These are the harshest conditions in the world for packaging tobacco products.
The Federal Government of Australia states that the aim of this measure is to discourage young people from smoking by depriving them of this harmful fashionable habit.
This decision was based on studies that showed that people who had not started smoking before the age of 26 had never become smokers in 99 cases out of 100.
“It is clear that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to communicate through packaging,” explains Health Minister Tanya Plybersec, citing studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess in children.
Australia was one of the countries with the lowest smoking rates in the world, so that changes would not affect the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries were already considering doing so.
The tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of the law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market in which cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
"This law will have serious consequences other than those intended by its initiators," says Scott McIntyre, a representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
The producers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply many more of these items for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the other hand, new laws encourage business growth.
Sandra Ha of a small family company, Zico Import Pty Ltd, claims that the demand for cigarette and silicone cases covering unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (practically from zero) since companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost their case in a high court in Australia, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about 6,000 items to wholesalers and is expecting a new shipment.
It's a good business for us.
In the view of experts, the popularity of social networks among the target population is a potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures.
Following the adoption of a number of laws in Australia that have made illegal television advertising of cigarettes and their support for sporting events and that prohibit vendors from displaying cigarettes, tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian Government has banned local companies and websites from placing advertisements online, but it cannot restrict overseas websites.
"If you're selling tobacco and you've only got this little loophole left, "the idea of promoting your product on the Internet would seem very tempting to you," says Becky Freeman, researching public health issues at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increasing number of brand reviews written on behalf of supposedly ordinary users on social media such as YouTube, Twitter, and Facebook.
The question is, is it really the work of a private citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he spared no effort and time and made a video, or is there an advertising company behind it?
British American Tobacco, Australia, claims that the industry is now more involved in adapting to the new rules than in advertising.
The tobacco industry had even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: those States were making claims in the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade had been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that all those countries had very little trade relations with Australia.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tani Plybersec, the Government was discussing with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada was the first to introduce mandatory smoking-risk photographs.
More than 40 countries now have this rule, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Great Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India are considering tightening their laws.
Many smokers in Australia are showing a lack of innovation.
These pictures don't bother me.
I just don't pay attention.
"Just taking a cigarette and hiding a pack in your pocket," explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a photograph of a mouth tumor on a pack.
To be honest, the only thing that can get me to leave is my little daughter.
James Yew, head of the tobacco store King of the Pack in downtown Sydney, claims that the same packaging made it more difficult to place goods in shelves.
"It took me an hour to unload the new shipment and now four hours," he complains.
"The government should have taken and banned cigarettes altogether, and we would have said, 'What do we do, okay, it's over, we close the store,' he says, throwing his hands up.
Boring in the world of electronic networks and permanent connections is not so bad.
On Thanksgiving, I suddenly had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had a mechanical malfunction and was replaced by another plane, which we waited for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and neither books, magazines, iPhones, nor even duty-free shops will help much.
However, more and more scholars and child development specialists have recently expressed their support for boredom.
They say that in certain situations it's not so bad for us and our children to miss.
This causes the brain to be distracted by interesting related topics, which may be conducive to creativity.
And because in today's world we're all constantly in front of some screen, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Perhaps we should seek boredom.
Yeah.
At the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
I used to think, like many people, that boredom was an invention of recent times, when people had more free time.
This is not the case, says Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at Calgary University of Canada, author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"In fact, boredom can boast of a very ancient story," he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are Latin signs of boredom dating back to the first century.
The question remains as to how we understand boredom.
The problem is, says John D. Eastwood, Associate Professor, University of York, Ontario, Canada, that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying the research on the subject and asking a 100-person target group, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: boredom is when people “want but cannot do what would please them”.
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn't do anything that he wants to do.
I don't want to do anything with apathy.
The main thing in the boredom, he says, is "the disruption of attention and the resulting deterioration of mood and the feeling that time is running slowly."
The description of boredom may seem quite like depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible connection between these states, bored people see the causes of the problems in the world and the circumstances around them, while depressed people see the problems in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored when it's just hard to focus on something.
In his study “The Unemployed Mind: A Definition of Boring from a Attention Point”, published in September's issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues refer to an earlier experiment where participants listened to a recording of the magazine's voice.
Some participants also heard loud sounds of an unrelated television program in the next room, others heard the same sounds in low volume, so that they could barely be broken down, and a third group listened only to the recording of the voice without a foreign sound track.
Those who heard TV with low volume said that they were bored, more often than not - they found it hard to concentrate, but they didn't know the reason and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or fascinating task, interruption can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Gvelf, Ontario, and one of the authors of this study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "for example, by looking at the flow of products on the conveyor in search of marriage, diversionary music can help avoid boredom."
It's believed that when people start swinging on a chair or drawing doodles on a piece of paper, they do so out of boredom, but now we know that in fact such actions simply help not to relax physically.
“The study has shown that children who are not prohibited from twirling and twirling learn better and remember more information than children who are asked to sit still,” says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we're all bored with the delayed flight (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
However, different people show different degrees of boredom.
In the 1980s, in order to measure such individual characteristics, researchers developed a special “breeding scale”.
Questions and assertions such as “Many of what I have to do is uniform and monotonous” or “I'm too interested in too much, so I'm running out of time” are used to measure this scale.
Using such questionnaires, researchers have found that boys miss more girls than girls, says Stephen Vodanovic, professor of psychology at the University of Western Florida, especially when there are a variety of external irritants.
In general, however, adolescents often miss each other.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment during which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with the help of a pager.
The results were as follows: 32 per cent of adolescents stated that they were bored at school and during their homework, and 23 per cent said that they were bored outside of school.
However, only 3% of parents indicated that they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no record of what this kind of data would be about boredom now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that “adolescents are at the height of boredom”, mainly because children and adolescents are not allowed to fully decide what to do.
Let's go back to my original question: is boredom helpful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme ways, research shows that it can push people into absurd and dangerous physical actions, risky gambling, or the abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovic, who has devoted more than two decades to the study of the problem.
"So our brain tells us to do something else; that's boredom," says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at New York University.
