The hardest job in the world: the Kawah-Igen miners
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulphur to the top of the volcano along steep rocky trails.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn a living from sulphur mining in the Kawah Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfur gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes in contact with the air.
Large pieces of sulfur, which can weigh as much as 70 kg, are placed in two bamboo baskets, put baskets on their shoulders, and carry them up on a broken rocky road.
To the top of the volcano, which is 2,386 metres high, only 250 metres are needed, but it takes more than 40 minutes for worn-out movers to rise up with a turtle’s foot, struggling to maintain balance and carefully push the road so that they do not fall off or fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong move could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the rocks of Cawah-Igen a few years ago.
The Kawah-Igen mine earns 5 Euro cents per kilogram of sulfur produced
Once they're up there, they lay a road between tourists who take pictures of them as if they were circus monkeys and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometres to the scales that the mining company placed just above, at an altitude of 1.850 metres.
This is PT Kandi Ngrimbi, an enterprise that has operated this volcano since 1960 and, better or less, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Euro cents) per kilogram of sulphur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 Euro cents) to petrochemicals, since this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even sugar bleaching.
“As the norm is to carry 70 kilograms, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) per walk”, Anto explains, who usually carries three daily hauls.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end feels broken, but they allow him to accumulate Rs. 138.000 (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a miser for such a inhuman effort, it's three times what he'd make in the field.
“The daily wages paid to miners are very high by local standards, with a coffee charge of Rs. 15,000 (Euro1.2) per day and an average monthly wage of Rs. 2 million (Euro167),” explains a loader who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
His salary there was Rs. 75,000 (Euro6.2) per day and the plot was not so heavy, but Anto returned with his family in Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a valid reason, which in Indonesia is as devastating as sulphur: “I married a girl from Bali, where only Hindus, and brought her to Java to accept Islam”.
Anto's asthma, he's barely breathing, he's coughing all the time, and his eyes are tearing because of the toxic gases.
At his 27th birthday, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kawah Igen, which had already begun to be sulfurized despite the presence of masks and special glasses.
He's got asthma, he's barely breathing, he's coughing all the time, and he's got eyes weeping because of the toxic gases that the volcano emits.
It's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'll work for two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punctuated by life, this nice and smart young man could be a tourist guide, a waiter, or a hotel clerk, but instead, he's doing mule work.
A dirty wooden cabin with other porters gets up every day at 2:00 a.m. because sulphur does not stop flowing at night when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glitters in the darkness.
By challenging the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, lighting his way with a small flashlight connected to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
About 400 porters are hauling baskets of gray on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano.
Despite the high profits, the mining company did not mechanize sulphur production to save costs, nor does it provide any equipment to porters who work on their own account and with such deprivation.
In fact, they do not receive even part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) charge for photography, which, together with the entry ticket for 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), guards of the reserve charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its mule people.
"This work is for cattle, not for people," says Badrusin, a native porter 42 years ago, who spent three decades in Kawah-Igen since leaving college.
Capable of raising to 110 kilos, he assures that he will tolerate work “as long as he can” because he needs money to educate his three children between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although the sulfur burns its throat and burns its eyes when the wind suddenly changes and catches miners in dense columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so resilient that no one complains about their serious illnesses... more serious, obviously than their usual breathing problems, arthrose, knee pains and shoulder ulcer, which have been deformed under the weight of the basket.
By balancing the basket on the back, Unanik can only raise 50 kilos in his 53s.
Each day, he and his companions carry 15 tons of sulphur out of the volcano, which three trucks transport to a warehouse in Tamansari, crossing a narrow trail of 18 kilometres across the bushes.
"I'm not going to retire, I'm going to die here because the volcano is my whole life," says Unanik, wide-opening a mouth that lacks a few teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30 years old, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest jobs in the world: what human mules from Kawah Igen do.
