UNASUR summit ends without the Lima Declaration
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without the promulgation of the Lima Declaration, which was announced earlier and theoretically signed by seven mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access a document signed at the VIth ordinary assembly of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Office of the President and the Office of the President indicated on the front page that it would be handed over after closure, but confirmed that it would be published on the Peruvian Government website at some point.
Questions about the text, they pointed out that the contents had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Umala, during brief press statements.
Journalists ' access to information on the Summit has always been limited.
During the day, it was only broadcast, in the press room, a video of the President's Assembly without a sound, with the message “closed meeting, no sound”.
Some of the information that has been distributed to reporters has been conveyed by UNASUR government spokespersons who were present at the meeting, but not from Peru.
The only document distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which caused dissatisfaction among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who requested more information.
Subsequently, the Peruvian President's administration sent an e-mail to the media with the “final declaration” of the summit, but this is the Umala statement, not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South American and Arab Summit (ASPA), and that time, despite the insistence of the press, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was also not disseminated.
The ASPA official website can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities had made efforts to ensure that all journalists were provided with transmission systems, but that information was as limited as possible.
The Summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to adopt a verdict of the Hague Court, which will settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Umala, and Chile, Sebastian Piñera, gathered at a regional meeting and ratified that they will abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which will begin hearing the statements of both parties on Monday in The Hague, in the context of the accusation that Lima has made against Santiago.
“We will respect and implement a decision that will explain the differences that we are now presenting to this international court”, Umala said, next to his Chilean colleague.
“Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of differences, covenants and international tribunals”, added Piñera, and welcomed the shaking of Umala's hand against the flags of those two countries.
The two Presidents' confirmation that they would be subject to the International Court of Justice came immediately after Colombia protested this week the Pact of Bogotá, according to which it recognized submission to the verdicts of the International Court of Justice following a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua, which it considered to be erroneous.
The Summit took place in the absence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Roussef; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR had been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The incoming President, Ollanta Umala, was responsible for opening discussions in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon in Lima time.
The Head of State read the outcome document, in which he reported that 16 agreements had been adopted and 31 projects had been approved among South American countries, with an estimated investment of $17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries would take “important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residence agreements”.
He reported that action was being taken to improve “co-operation in the fight against citizen insecurity and organized transnational crime, actions to increase access to medicines, low-cost Internet access in all parts of South America and to take into account the combined and effective risks of natural disasters”.
Since Europe is in crisis, “the economic union (Latin America) should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to broaden our production base and anticipate a better future for our cities”, Umala added.
“We have decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connectivity of South America, especially in the village and border zones... unifying our countries and forming new economic schemes,” said the Peruvian President in a read-out.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five related to Peru and were limited to cross-axis on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two aimed at a greater link with Ecuador, but he did not provide any more details.
The outcome document also addressed the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve its re-accession to the Union of South American Nations, from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of well-being and peace, to be united and to have good relations among neighbours, was another theme emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before attending the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his colleague from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to negotiate in a respectful manner the maritime dispute as a result of the verdict of the international court challenged by Bogotá.
"The day after tomorrow (Saturday), perhaps I'll meet President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
“Let us reconsider all these ways, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua”, he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we can handle this in the most civilized and respectful manner possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico City on Saturday, where they will have a new President, Enrique Peña Nieto, present at the inauguration.
Also within the framework of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc met in advance for the adoption of the 2013 Action Plan, which is aimed at strengthening dialogue and consensus on the protection of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay constitute UNASUR, although the latter has been suspended.
Peru has a temporary presidency in the regional bloc.
