AIDS mortality today is the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was told that his AIDS test had been positive.
"I've been stunned," he recalls, despite all the doctor's tact, the moment.
The boy hid it from his family.
Having decided to deal with the disease on his own, he wanted to know as much about it as possible, and his efforts were justified - he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the “oldest” patients of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG) HIV hospital, where he entered in 1994, and has overcome many obstacles.
He's been diagnosed with a human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, and in the early 1990s it would be hard to believe that there were too few treatment options, too little knowledge of the disease, too much prejudice towards the sick.
So even the director of the clinic at the Mexican Social Security Institute didn't want to say goodbye to him, "because he had a cut."
In other words, it was a sentence to have AIDS in those days.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so without compromising the quality of life.
Yet, unaware of their illness, many people still come when the virus has already caused damage, “destroyed” their immune system and suffer from opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least after the first reported cases, “the greatest achievement to date is that the survival of a patient who begins treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population is exactly the same”, pointed out the head of HCHG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, referring to the fact that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectionist and HIV/AIDS expert, Andrade Villanueva, explained that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a sentence, but that life expectancy and quality of life depended on the degree of immune system failure that patients had at the beginning of their diagnosis, with better life expectancy for those who did not use drugs: up to 30 years with 200 CD4 and up to 50 years when 500 CD4 was reported.
Simply put, the above means that a person who is diagnosed with HIV positive at 25 years of age, according to these terms, “maintaining control will be able to live without problems up to 75 years of age”, he explained.
To assess this progress, it should be recalled that Mexicans now have an average life expectancy of 76 years.
Although mortality has declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has declined from 6.678 in 2007 to 4.862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that 60 per cent of patients in the national database have died since AIDS.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths have already been recorded by May this year; however, it is claimed that there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why is there still a death toll?
Personally, I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I picture it, that's how things are at our hospital.
At least for the last 12 years, we haven't had a shortage of medication, the problem is that patients come very late because they don't know about their infected condition, that is, in the late stages of the disease.
He cited devastating data: “Nine out of ten patients come when they already have some sort of opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to perform diagnostics at an earlier stage, and therefore it is necessary to provide mass detection samples for all people who request it.”
The proposal agreed with the experts and officials of the State AIDS Prevention Council in Jalisco (COESIDA), as well as the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who went to a private laboratory for inspection, motivated only by the fact that his friend had done it and, despite his young age, he had already been in the AIDS phase and even suffered from Kaposha sarcoma, a cancer that was a common complication.
Things change when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're gonna die, and they don't want to know.
"If I die anyway, I'd rather get drunk three times a week," they say, but not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, do exercise, take medication.
To date, his parents only know that he's had cancer.
I live a normal life like any other.
"I work, I do a lot of work, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, I care about myself and another person," listed Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO to encourage his statement to those who now fear in the context of World AIDS Day.
Let them check if there was a risk of infection, let them know as soon as possible if they're HIV positive, that's better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them know that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
His presentation summarizes the theme of the fight against AIDS this year 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara, believes that there is a great gap between health programmes and a common citizen who has taken up the issue of HIV.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, “the distribution of condoms has actually increased, we've been given one or two before, and now we're given 100 bags, and that's very good, but it turns out that there are those who still don't have access to the condom”, he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"Why do you want them?" is a popular question, with escapism and condemnation from social workers, school counselors, pharmacists and health workers who don't want teenagers to hear, assured the promoter.
I suggest that we change this inefficient distribution; that condoms be not just behind counters and that hundreds of them be in machine guns in public toilets in places frequented by young people.
It's not about encouraging promiscuity.
It was not a question of paying for beer and a motel, and Governor Emilio Gonzalez responded when asked if it was possible to distribute condoms under his leadership.
"It's not sexuality, it's best to make condoms available to those who already practice sexual activity," he said.
Key data in Jalisco
A total of 13.435 cases (12.158 AIDS and 1.317 HIV cases) have been registered.
The state ranks fourth in the national ranking for new and total AIDS cases and thirteenth in HIV cases.
92% of the infections are in the course of sex, 6% through blood, and 2% through the perinatal route.
